body:
Hello!
... and the code either works as in Icarus Verilog, or not.
Perhaps, this is rare case. But I'm using HDL which generates such Verilog code and now I'm blocked by verilator :(

Verilator 5.035 devel rev v5.034-88-g8965401d1

Consider this example:
```
$ cat a.v
module test;
	initial begin
		a = 0;
	end
	reg a;
	always @(*) begin
		a <= 0;
		if (a == 0) begin
			$display("a == 0");
		end
		if (a == 1) begin
			$display("a == 1");
		end
		a <= 1;
	end
endmodule
```

```
verilator -Wno-fatal --cc --top test a.v
```

It seems, verilator sees "a <= 0" and optimizes everything out and generates this code (which gives different result than Icarus Verilog):
```
VL_ATTR_COLD void Vtest___024root___eval_initial__TOP(Vtest___024root* vlSelf) {
    VL_DEBUG_IF(VL_DBG_MSGF("+    Vtest___024root___eval_initial__TOP\n"); );
    Vtest__Syms* const __restrict vlSymsp VL_ATTR_UNUSED = vlSelf->vlSymsp;
    auto& vlSelfRef = std::ref(*vlSelf).get();
    // Body
    VL_WRITEF_NX("a == 0\n",0);
}
```

If I move "a <= 0" after (below) the if's:
```
module test;
	initial begin
		a = 0;
	end
	reg a;
	always @(*) begin
		if (a == 0) begin
			$display("a == 0");
		end
		if (a == 1) begin
			$display("a == 1");
		end
		a <= 0;
		a <= 1;
	end
endmodule
```

then verilator generates another code (which gives the same result as Icarus Verilog):
```
VL_INLINE_OPT void Vtest___024root___act_sequent__TOP__0(Vtest___024root* vlSelf) {
    VL_DEBUG_IF(VL_DBG_MSGF("+    Vtest___024root___act_sequent__TOP__0\n"); );
    Vtest__Syms* const __restrict vlSymsp VL_ATTR_UNUSED = vlSelf->vlSymsp;
    auto& vlSelfRef = std::ref(*vlSelf).get();
    // Body
    if (VL_UNLIKELY(((1U & (~ (IData)(vlSelfRef.test__DOT__a)))))) {
        VL_WRITEF_NX("a == 0\n",0);
    }
    if (VL_UNLIKELY((vlSelfRef.test__DOT__a))) {
        VL_WRITEF_NX("a == 1\n",0);
    }
    vlSelfRef.test__DOT__a = 1U;
}
```

Icarus Verilog gives the same result regardless of the "a <= 0" location, but verilator generates different code with different outcome.
I suppose, Icarus Verilog behaves correctly, but verilator does not.
Will it be difficult to fix this?

